entry.et: Middle English strete, from Old English strǣt, from Late Latin strata paved road, from Latin, feminine of stratus, past participle stratum

def.dt: :a thoroughfare especially in a city, town, or village that is wider than an alley or lane and that usually includes sidewalks
:the part of a street reserved for vehicles
:a thoroughfare with abutting property lives on a fashionable street
:the people occupying property on a street the whole street knew about the accident
:a promising line of development or a channeling of effort a crafty politician working both sides of the street success through compromise is a two-way street
:a district (as Wall Street or Fleet Street) identified with a particular profession
:the people who work in such a district doing better than the Street expected
:an environment (as in a depressed neighborhood or section of a city) of poverty, dereliction, or crime grew up on the mean streets
:idle, homeless, or out of a job
:out of prison :at liberty
:suited to one's abilities or taste
:of or relating to the streets: as
:adjoining or giving access to a street the street door
:carried on or taking place in the street street fighting
:living or working on the streets a street peddler street people
:located in, used for, or serving as a guide to the streets a street map
:performing in or heard on the street a street band
:suitable for wear or use on the street street clothes
:not touching the ground used of a woman's dress in lengths reaching the knee, calf, or ankle
:of, relating to, or characteristic of the street environment street drugs used … his new street cred to develop contacts Dale Keiger
:retail the street price
:a tough belligerent person a political street fighter
:a game resembling ice hockey played on a hard surface by players wearing shoes or roller skates and using hockey sticks and a small ball
:a line operating streetcars or buses
:streetwise
:the quality of being streetwise
:drama dealing with controversial social and political issues that is usually performed outdoors
:civilian life
:a row of cumulus clouds
